      #Summary
      We want you to change the world.

      How do we help you do that? You want a meaningful career that makes a real difference. But you face a tough career decision: What job should I take? Should I do further study? Should I leave my job for one that does more to help the world?

      We think the conventional advice [isn’t good enough](http://80000hours.org/blog/183-the-worst-ethical-careers-advice-in-the-world).

      We’re the first organisation that helps you answer: *how can I use the 80,000 hours of my career to make the most difference?*, that is, how can I help the most people, in the biggest ways, now and into the future? We identify the most pressing problems in the world, and work out how you can do the most to solve them using your career. Our recommendations are based on in-depth research and transparent, rigorous analysis, conducted with help from the leading experts and academics at Oxford.

      This page contains the most useful results we have learned from analysing the decisions of hundreds of people in our [coaching process](/coaching/overview) and our independent research. 

      * * *

      #High Impact Careers

      In which careers can you make the most impact? We’ve made a [basic framework to help you compare your options.](http://80000hours.org/blog/238-how-to-assess-the-impact-of-a-career)

      ![Career Value Equation](/assets/pages/research/career_value.png)

      We think valuable careers do two key things. First, they have a positive impact. Second, they give you better, flexible options to have an impact in the future, which we call your ‘career capital.’

      **High impact careers move lots of resources into effective solutions to pressing problems**. So, look for options that give you lots of leverage (whether that consists of campaigning, research, money, or something else) and let you help effective causes (see below for more on that).

      When assessing **career capital**, look for what you gain in terms of (i) skills (ii) connections, and (iii) useful credentials.

      * * *

      #Effective Causes
      Which causes are most high priority?

      ![Cause Effectiveness](/assets/pages/research/cause-effectiveness.png)


      You can use our framework for assessing causes to work out, given your values, in which causes are most effective.

      Some problems are important but not solvable. Others are solvable but [not important](http://qz.com/84943/what-we-can-learn-from-one-of-the-worst-charities-in-the-world/). The most effective causes involve **problems that are both solvable and important**.

      Broadly, you could think of the most important causes as the ones that can benefit the **most people** in the **biggest ways** in the **long-term**. Though, some causes are important due to their indirect impact - they let you learn about what’s effective and help us make progress in other areas.

      When looking for solvable causes, look for:
      * Clear ways to make progress supported by strong evidence or theory
      * A pressing need for more people working on the cause, and a theory about why the cause doesn’t get enough support.
      * A track record of success in similar causes

