      #Personal Fit
      
      Which option is the best fit for you?

      We don’t think ‘do what you’re passionate about’ or ‘do what you’re good at’ is [very useful advice](http://80000hours.org/blog/183-the-worst-ethical-careers-advice-in-the-world) . Passion and ability develop out of dedicating yourself to a skill, so it’s better plan the other way round, and ask yourself “what do I *want* to become good at?” You’ve probably got more good options open to you than you think. 

      How can you decide what you want to become good at? Ask “what can I do that’s most valuable for the world?” Putting [the value you create for others first](http://80000hours.org/blog/187-the-best-career-advice-you-ll-never-hear-in-a-graduation-speech) can lead to a deeply fulfilling career. 

      When it comes to comparing jobs, we think people [worry too much](http://80000hours.org/blog/243-does-your-personality-matter-in-picking-a-career) about whether their personality is a “good fit” for certain jobs. To find a meaningful job, what [really matters](http://80000hours.org/blog/134-our-research-on-how-to-find-a-job-you-love) is interesting work, with purpose and good support from your colleagues.

      Beyond that, much depends on the details of the situation, which is why we offer [one-on-one coaching](/coaching/overview). Further, there’s still plenty that’s not known about how to fit people with jobs, so make sure you try lots of things out!

      * * *

      #Your Plan

      Having a plan is useful for motivation and direction, but overly [rigid plans](http://80000hours.org/blog/164-should-you-plan-your-career) quickly  go out of date and make you inflexible. We’ve developed a style of career plan that we think strikes a good balance. You can [start applying our career model](http://80000hours.org/blog/241-introduction-to-our-career-model) to your own career.

      Don’t get caught up in thinking your decision to be perfect. Rather, treat everything as a [best guess](http://80000hours.org/blog/237-your-career-is-like-a-startup), that you’re going to refine and test as time goes on.

      There are [important biases](http://80000hours.org/blog/165-biases-how-they-affect-your-career-decisions-and-what-to-do-about-them) to avoid too. You’ll probably consider too few options and be biased to stay on your current path. Going with your gut can be useful sometimes, but often it’s better to be more systematic.

